  "description": "Addition is the most basic operation in arithmetic — it combines two quantities into their total. Three apples plus two apples is five apples. The idea is so intuitive that children learn it before they can read. But formalizing addition — specifying exactly what it means and proving that it works as expected — requires care, because addition is the foundation on which the rest of arithmetic is built.\nIn the formal development of the natural numbers through the Peano axioms, addition is defined recursively using the successor function SS (the function that takes each number to the next one). Two rules suffice: n+0=nn + 0 = n (adding zero does nothing), and n+S(m)=S(n+m)n + S(m) = S(n + m) (adding the successor of mm is the successor of adding mm). Together with the induction principle, these two clauses determine the sum of any two natural numbers. To compute 3+23 + 2, for example: 3+2=3+S(1)=S(3+1)=S(3+S(0))=S(S(3+0))=S(S(3))=S(4)=53 + 2 = 3 + S(1) = S(3 + 1) = S(3 + S(0)) = S(S(3 + 0)) = S(S(3)) = S(4) = 5.\n",
